{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517929"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:58:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12851"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12851"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.71,0.07,0.02,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5294"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50385"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5294"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35614"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"99"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"2492"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9589"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43358"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50385"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the GP clinic with a three month history of increasing shortness of breath. His symptoms are worse on lying flat and often wakes him at night. His medical history includes hypertension and ischaemic heart disease, with coronary artery bypass surgery eight years ago. He is an active smoker with 40 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his temperature is 36.9\u00baC, blood pressure 152/98mmHg, pulse 80/min and an SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E of 95% on room air. He has a pansystolic murmur loudest at the mitral area with radiation to the axilla. He has bilateral pitting oedema to the knees. His chest is clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA recent transthoracic echocardiogram records an estimated pulmonary artery systolic pressure of 60mmHg. A CT chest is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apixaban","Furosemide","Epoprostenol","Oxygen therapy","Bosentan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has pulmonary hypertension, given his estimated pulmonary artery systolic pressure of 60mmHg. Pulmonary hypertension (PH) is defined as mean pulmonary artery pressure \u003Cstrong\u003E\u226520\u00a0mm Hg at rest. \u003C/strong\u003EThis can be classified into five groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 1: Pulmonary arterial hypertension (e.g. idiopathic, familial, drug and toxin induced)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 2: Secondary to left-sided heart disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 3: Secondary to pulmonary disease or hypoxia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 4: Secondary to chronic thromboembolism\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 5: Unclear, multifactorial aetiologies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor this patient, he has Group 2 pulmonary hypertension - pulmonary hypertension due to left-sided heart disease. He likely has severe mitral regurgitation contributing to left sided heart failure. This explains his dyspnoea, orthopnoea and paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnoea. He requires management of his left ventricular failure to manage his pulmonary hypertension, and hence \u003Cstrong\u003Efurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EThe groups of pulmonary hypertension are important because they guide treatment.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 1 (Pulmonary arterial hypertension - PAH) can be treated with \u003Cstrong\u003Eepoprostenol \u003C/strong\u003Eor\u003Cstrong\u003E bosentan. Epoprostenol\u003C/strong\u003E is a prostacyclin derivative which promotes vasodilation and antiproliferation. \u003Cstrong\u003EBosentan\u003C/strong\u003E is an endothelin receptor antagonist which inhibits pulmonary vasoconstriction. Neither of these medications are used in Group 2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 3 (pulmonary hypertension due to lung diseases and/or hypoxia) can be treated with inhalers and \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient may have COPD given his smoking history, but this is less likely the cause of his pulmonary hypertension because his CT chest is unremarkable. \u003Cstrong\u003EPDE5 inhibitors \u003C/strong\u003Emay also be trialled in patients with severe PH associated with ILD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGroup 4 (chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension CTEPH) can be treated with lifelong anticoagulation. Usually this is with warfarin rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eapixaban\u003C/strong\u003E. Anticoagulation is not usually used to treat Group 2, but needs to be considered for co-existing diagnoses such as atrial fibrillation. Furthermore, surgical management or balloon pulmonary angioplasty may be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Understand the different WHO Classes of pulmonary hypertension"],"references":["Marc Humbert and others, 2022 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension: Developed by the task force for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC) and the European Respiratory Society (ERS). Endorsed by the International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation (ISHLT) and the European Reference Network on rare respiratory diseases (ERN-LUNG)., European Heart Journal, Volume 43, Issue 38, 7 October 2022, Pages 3618\u20133731, https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehac237"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35614"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12851"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35614"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-11T11:14:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-11T11:14:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5294"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50385"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"d